@@ -0,0 +1,287 @@
+# Sen installer
+
+Quick-install path for Sen. Downloads a release build into your home
+directory and writes a small activate script you source from your shell. No
+Conan, no sudo, no system files touched.
+
+This directory is meant for end users who want to *try* Sen without setting
+up Conan; for real projects, use the Conan package.
+
+## Quick install
+
+```sh
+curl -sSf https://raw.githubusercontent.com/airbus/sen/main/resources/installer/install.sh | sh
+```
+
+With no version argument the script lists the available releases. Pass one
+to install it:
+
+```sh
+curl -sSf .../install.sh | sh -s -- 0.5.2
+curl -sSf .../install.sh | sh -s -- 0.5.2 --compiler gcc-12.4.0
+curl -sSf .../install.sh | sh -s -- 0.5.2 --yes        # non-interactive
+```
+
+After the first install the script self-copies to `$SEN_HOME/install.sh`,
+so subsequent installs skip the bootstrap fetch (the GitHub API and the
+tarball still need network):
+
+```sh
+sh ~/.sen/install.sh 0.6.0
+```
+
+## What gets installed where
+
+```
+~/.sen/
+  <build-id>/                            # e.g. 0.5.2-x86_64-linux-gcc-12.4.0
+    bin/  lib/  include/  share/
+    activate                             # source from bash / zsh
+    activate.fish                        # source from fish
+    .sen-manifest.sha256                 # generated at install time
+    share/sen-completions/{bash,zsh,fish}
+  cache/
+    sen-<...>-release.tar.gz             # downloaded archives
+  install.sh                             # self-copied installer
+```
+
+The `cache/` directory keeps downloaded tarballs across installs. If a
+re-install needs an archive that's still in the cache (you removed
+`<build-id>/` and re-ran), `fetch_archive` reuses it; if the release publishes
+a `SHA256SUMS` file, `verify_checksum` then catches a corrupted cache and
+forces a re-download. Safe to prune at any time with `rm ~/.sen/cache/*`.
+
+Multiple builds can coexist (different versions, different toolchains).
+Switching is "source the other build's activate"; the activate scripts strip
+any prior `~/.sen/`-rooted entries from `PATH`, `CMAKE_PREFIX_PATH`,
+`PKG_CONFIG_PATH`, and `LD_LIBRARY_PATH` before prepending the new one, so
+re-sourcing or switching is idempotent.
+
+## Activating a build
+
+```sh
+. ~/.sen/0.5.2-x86_64-linux-gcc-12.4.0/activate          # bash / zsh
+source ~/.sen/0.5.2-x86_64-linux-gcc-12.4.0/activate.fish # fish
+```
+
+To load Sen on every new shell, append the same line to your rc file
+(`~/.bashrc`, `~/.zshrc`, `~/.config/fish/config.fish`).
+
+To leave the env in this shell, open a fresh shell or `exec $SHELL`. We do
+not ship a deactivate function; one shell command is cheaper than the code
+to maintain a clean unset path.
+
+## Exit codes
+
+| Code | Meaning                                                        |
+| ---- | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
+| 0    | success (or already installed)                                 |
+| 1    | any failure: bad args, missing tooling, network, extract, ...  |
+| 99   | another `install.sh` is in progress (the install lock)         |
+
+## Environment variables
+
+| Variable           | Default                                                  | Purpose                                            |
+| ------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------- |
+| `SEN_HOME`         | `$HOME/.sen`                                             | Install root                                       |
+| `SEN_BASE_URL`     | `https://github.com/airbus/sen`                          | Base for release downloads                         |
+| `SEN_API_URL`      | `https://api.github.com/repos/airbus/sen`                | Base for the GitHub Releases API                   |
+| `SEN_RAW_URL`      | `https://raw.githubusercontent.com/airbus/sen/main`      | Where the self-copy refetches `install.sh` from    |
+| `SEN_ALLOW_ROOT`   | unset                                                    | Set to `1` to allow running as root (containers)   |
+| `NO_COLOR`         | unset                                                    | Set to disable color output                        |
+| `SEN_DEV_STRICT`   | unset                                                    | Test runner: fail if optional tooling is missing   |
+
+## Security model
+
+The installer puts Sen builds into your home directory. It does not modify
+system files, does not run as root by default, and does not install anything
+outside `$SEN_HOME`. The guarantees beyond that are bounded by what we
+verify and what we trust; this section names both.
+
+### What we trust
+
+- **TLS to GitHub.** All downloads (the release JSON, asset tarballs,
+  optional `SHA256SUMS`, the `install.sh` we self-copy) go through
+  `https://`. We rely on the system's trusted-cert store; we do not pin
+  certificates.
+- **The Sen binaries you install.** After install, files under
+  `<prefix>/bin` are on your `PATH` and are invoked by Sen-aware tools
+  (CMake `find_package`, the `term` CLI, etc.). The activate script
+  evaluates a pre-rendered shell-completion script we wrote at install
+  time. If the build itself is compromised, those evaluations give it
+  shell access.
+- **The activate scripts.** Anyone with write access to `<prefix>/activate`
+  or `<prefix>/activate.fish` can compromise every shell that sources them.
+
+### What we verify
+
+- **Optional release-side checksums.** When a release publishes a
+  `SHA256SUMS` file alongside its archives, the installer verifies the
+  downloaded archive against it. If the release does not publish one,
+  installation proceeds with a soft note.
+- **Per-install local manifest.** At install time `install.sh` writes
+  `<prefix>/.sen-manifest.sha256` covering every file in the build tree
+  (excluding the manifest itself and the activate scripts, which are
+  generated after extraction). Verify by hand any time:
+  ```sh
+  cd ~/.sen/<build-id> && sha256sum -c .sen-manifest.sha256
+  ```
+  The manifest is not signed; it defends against accidental corruption
+  (failed update, partial restore, filesystem error), not against an
+  attacker who can also modify the manifest.
+
+### What we explicitly do not protect against
+
+- **A compromised release pipeline.** If Sen's CI is compromised and
+  publishes a malicious build, the release-side `SHA256SUMS` will match
+  the malicious bytes. We have no out-of-band signing (GPG, minisign,
+  cosign) today.
+- **MITM at the certificate-trust level.** A user whose CA store has been
+  tampered with would not be detected.
+- **Local tampering.** Anything with write access to `$SEN_HOME` can
+  drop a malicious binary into a build prefix; the activate script will
+  put it on your `PATH` next time you source it.
+
+## Compatibility hint
+
+Before installing, the script checks `gcc -dumpfullversion -dumpversion`
+(or `clang -dumpversion`) and shows a soft warning if the build's compiler
+version differs from yours. The warning never blocks; ABI mismatches
+generally fail at link time anyway. glibc detection is on the roadmap; for
+now, mismatched glibc versions show up as runtime errors.
+
+## Supported shells
+
+First-class support, tested in CI:
+
+| Shell  | Minimum version | Activate file                          |
+| ------ | --------------- | -------------------------------------- |
+| bash   | 4+              | `<prefix>/activate`                    |
+| zsh    | 5+              | `<prefix>/activate`                    |
+| fish   | 3+              | `<prefix>/activate.fish`               |
+
+The bootstrap (`install.sh`) itself is POSIX `sh` and runs under any POSIX
+shell (dash, busybox ash, bash, ...). It has no shell-specific dependencies.
+
+For ksh, tcsh, nushell, elvish, xonsh, or PowerShell, community
+contributions are welcome; we don't actively maintain them. The variables
+the activate scripts set (`PATH`, `CMAKE_PREFIX_PATH`, `PKG_CONFIG_PATH`,
+`LD_LIBRARY_PATH`, `SEN_PREFIX`) are exported as standard env vars, so
+adapting the activate logic to another shell is a small piece of work.
+
+## Multi-compiler / multi-arch handling
+
+A release may ship several builds for the same Sen version (gcc-12.4.0,
+gcc-13.2.0, clang-16.0.0 side by side). The installer:
+
+- detects the host's `(arch, os)` from `uname -m` / `uname -s` and filters
+  the release's asset list to matching candidates;
+- if exactly one candidate remains, installs it;
+- if several remain (e.g. multiple compilers for one arch), falls back to
+  the interactive menu, or refuses with `--yes` and tells the caller which
+  toolchains exist;
+- `--compiler` accepts `gcc-<ver>`, `clang-<ver>`, `msvc-<ver>`, or a bare
+  `<ver>` (treated as `gcc-<ver>` for backward compatibility with the
+  pre-0.6 filename convention).
+
+The compat hint at the bottom of the menu compares each candidate against
+the matching compiler on the host (gcc and clang are auto-detected). For
+toolchains we don't know how to detect natively, the marker reads "(no
+&lt;name&gt; on your system)".
+
+## Known limitations
+
+- **Linux only.** macOS and Windows are not in scope for this installer
+  today; we filter assets to `linux` regardless of host. Architecture is
+  derived dynamically from `uname -m`. There is no hardcoded arch list,
+  so x86_64, aarch64, ppc64le, riscv64, or anything else works the moment
+  a matching release artifact exists.
+- **Requires `curl`.** Hard requirement; `apt install curl` (or the
+  equivalent for your distro) if it's missing.
+- **No GPG / minisign signing** of artifacts. We rely on TLS for transport
+  integrity. Optional `SHA256SUMS` verification is supported and silently
+  skipped if the release doesn't publish one.
+
+## Uninstall
+
+```sh
+rm -rf ~/.sen/<build-id>     # one build
+rm -rf ~/.sen                # everything (builds, cache, install.sh)
+```
+
+Then remove the `source ...activate` line from your shell rc.
+
+## Development
+
+The installer ships a single file:
+
+- `install.sh`: POSIX `sh` script. Contains the install pipeline (resolve
+  URL, optional menu, fetch, verify, extract, manifest, completions cache)
+  and the embedded activate-script templates (one POSIX, one fish-native).
+
+Tests live in `test/`. Run from this directory:
+
+```sh
+sh test/run.sh
+```
+
+`run.sh` uses `bats-core` if it's available and otherwise prints a warning
+and runs only the deps-free checks (syntax). To make a missing `bats` a
+hard error (intended for CI), set `SEN_DEV_STRICT=1`.
+
+The Sen Docker dev image (in the separate `sen-docker` repo) ships with
+`bats`, `curl`, `dash`, and `fish`, so the canonical dev path runs the full
+suite.
+
+## Shell idioms cheat sheet
+
+If you don't write a lot of shell, these are the patterns you'll meet most
+often when reading `install.sh`. POSIX-portable unless flagged otherwise.
+
+### Parameter expansion (no command spawned)
+
+| Idiom              | What it does                                           | Example                                            |
+| ------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------- |
+| `${var:-default}`  | value of `$var`, or `default` if unset / empty         | `${NO_COLOR:-}`                                    |
+| `${var:+x}`        | `x` if `$var` is non-empty, otherwise nothing          | `${out:+:$out}` prepends `:` only if `$out` is set |
+| `${var#prefix}`    | strip shortest matching prefix                         | `${stem#sen-}` gives `0.5.2-...` from `sen-0.5.2-...` |
+| `${var##prefix}`   | strip *longest* matching prefix (greedy)               | `${path##*/}` is the basename                      |
+| `${var%suffix}`    | strip shortest matching suffix                         | `${name%-release.tar.gz}`                          |
+| `${var%%suffix}`   | strip *longest* matching suffix (greedy)               | `${rest%%:*}` gives the part before the first `:`  |
+
+### Tests and conditionals
+
+| Idiom              | What it does                                            |
+| ------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------- |
+| `[ -z "$x" ]`      | true if `$x` is empty                                   |
+| `[ -n "$x" ]`      | true if `$x` is non-empty                               |
+| `[ -t 1 ]`         | true if file descriptor 1 (stdout) is a terminal        |
+| `[ -d "$p" ]`      | true if `$p` is a directory                             |
+| `[ -f "$p" ]`      | true if `$p` is a regular file                          |
+| `[ -r "$p" ]`      | true if `$p` is readable                                |
+| `[ "$a" = "$b" ]`  | string equality (note: single `=`, single `[`)          |
+| `cmd && other`     | run `other` only if `cmd` succeeds                      |
+| `cmd \|\| other`   | run `other` only if `cmd` fails                         |
+
+### Other essentials
+
+| Idiom                    | What it does                                                                                |
+| ------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
+| `command -v foo`         | POSIX way to test "is `foo` callable"; replaces the non-portable `which foo`                |
+| `local x="$1"`           | inside a function, declares `x` function-scoped (not POSIX, but bash/zsh/dash all support)  |
+| `printf '%s\n' "$x"`     | safer than `echo` (which has portability surprises with `-n`, `-e`, backslashes)            |
+| `2>/dev/null`            | redirect stderr to the void                                                                 |
+| `>&2`                    | redirect stdout of *this* command to stderr                                                 |
+| `cmd 2>&1`               | merge stderr into stdout                                                                    |
+| `<<EOF ... EOF`          | heredoc; feeds the lines between as stdin to the preceding command                          |
+| `$(cmd)`                 | command substitution: capture `cmd`'s stdout                                                |
+| `$$`                     | the current shell's process ID; we use it as a uniqueness suffix on temp dirs               |
+| `$@` / `$#`              | the script's positional arguments / their count                                             |
+| `set -eu`                | strict mode: fail on any error, fail on undefined variable                                  |
+
+### bash/zsh portability notes
+
+- **`<(cmd)` (process substitution)**: bash and zsh, but **not** POSIX/dash.
+  We don't use it; `install.sh` stays POSIX.
+- **`[[ ... ]]`**: bash and zsh extension; we use plain `[ ]` for portability.
+- **bash arrays (`arr=()`, `${arr[@]}`)**: bash; we don't use them.
